  "text": "In Kubernetes, controller registration follows a structured pattern distinct from sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime. Controllers in kubernetes/kubernetes are registered and managed through a manager pattern that uses shared informer factories and a controller context.\n\n## Key Registration Components\n\n### 1. Controller Interface Definition\nThe base `Interface` type is defined in `staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go`. This interface defines the minimal contract for a controller with a `Name()` method. Controllers can optionally implement the `Debuggable` interface (providing debugging handlers) and `HealthCheckable` interface (providing health checks).\n\n### 2. Controller Manager Context\nThe `ControllerContext` in `staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/app/controllercontext.go` acts as the manager, providing:\n- `ClientBuilder`: for creating Kubernetes API clients\n- `InformerFactory`: for sharing informers across controllers\n- `ObjectOrMetadataInformerFactory`: for generic controller access\n- `RESTMapper`: for REST resource mapping\n- `Stop` channel: for graceful shutdown\n- `InformersStarted` signal: for controller synchronization\n\n### 3. Reconciler Patterns\nMultiple reconciler implementations demonstrate the reconciliation loop pattern:\n- `pkg/kubelet/pluginmanager/reconciler/reconciler.go` defines a `Reconciler` interface with a `Run()` method\n- `pkg/controller/volume/attachdetach/reconciler/reconciler.go` implements reconciliation for volume attach/detach\n- `pkg/controlplane/reconcilers/reconcilers.go` defines `EndpointReconciler` for managing API server endpoints\n\nThese reconcilers run periodic loops that reconcile desired state with actual state.\n\n### 4. Sample Controller Registration Flow\nThe `staging/src/k8s.io/sample-controller/` demonstrates the standard pattern:\n\n**Initialization** (`main.go`):\n1. Create informer factories: `kubeinformers.NewSharedInformerFactory()` and custom informer factories\n2. Create the controller: `NewController(ctx, kubeClient, exampleClient, informers...)`\n3. Start informer factories: `kubeInformerFactory.Start(ctx.Done())`\n4. Run the controller: `controller.Run(ctx, workerCount)`\n\n**Controller Structure** (`controller.go`):\n- `NewController()` initializes the Controller struct with clients, listers, and work queue\n- Sets up event handlers on informers to queue work items when resources change\n- `Run()` method waits for cache sync, then starts worker goroutines\n- `syncHandler()` is the main reconciliation method that compares desired vs actual state\n\n### 5. Main Controller Manager\nThe `cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go` file implements the main entry point that:\n1. Creates a `ControllerContext` with shared informers and clients\n2. Orchestrates starting multiple controllers in the manager\n3. Uses `leader election` for HA setups\n4. Manages the lifecycle of all controllers through the main `Run()` function\n\n## Registration Summary\n\nUnlike sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime which uses a `SetupWithManager()` pattern, Kubernetes controllers register themselves by:\n1. Implementing the `Interface` interface with a `Name()` method\n2. Accepting a `ControllerContext` containing shared resources (informers, clients)\n3. Implementing a `Run(ctx context.Context, ...)` method that starts the reconciliation loop\n4. Setting up event handlers on informers to populate a work queue\n5. Processing items from the work queue in worker goroutines, calling the sync handler\n\nThe manager (embodied by the controller manager process and the ControllerContext) is responsible for:\n- Creating and configuring shared informer factories\n- Providing clients and REST mappers to controllers\n- Coordinating informer startup and controller initialization\n- Managing graceful shutdown through context cancellation\n- Handling leader election for HA deployments"
}

